n, John Patrick, Kieran, Siobhan, Tiernan.","Irish (Cork): from Gaelic <b>Ó Ceallacháin</b>, see   Callahan  ."]}]},{"name":"Margred","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Margaret</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Mared","meanings":["Simplified form of   Marged ."]}]},{"name":"daughter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London): variant of <b>Dafter</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, apparently from Middle English <i>doughter</i>, <i>dohtor</i>, <i>douter</i> (Old English <i>dohtor</i>) ‘daughter’, often pronounced in early modern English as <i>dafter</i>. For the name to be borne by a man, such that it became a hereditary surname, is surprising, though there are occasional instances of men being named in this way (unless they are clerical errors or it was a surname acquired by the retainers of an heiress of an important family). Alternatively, alternatively <i>Daughter</i>, <i>Daughters</i> might be a simplified pronunciation of <b>Dawtry</b> (see   Daughtery  ), a surname well evidenced in Yorkshire and Sussex, where <i>Doughter</i> and <i>Daughter</i> also occur, in which case the change to <i>Dafter</i> will have arisen through misinterpretation."],"variants":[{"name":"Daughtery","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Dawtrey</b>, see   Daughtry   and also   Daughters  . The surname is most common in Yorkshire and Sussex, where the medieval <i>Dawtrey</i> family held lands in the 12th century."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1352858,"age":83,"year":"1519","julianDay":2275863,"description":"Charles I of Spain became Emperor Charles V of the Holy Roman Empire.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margred daughter of Owain was born about 1436, in Wales, her father, Owain ap Ieuan, was 23 and her mother, Mawd Ferch Cadwaladr, was -68. She had at least 1 daughter with Hywel Roger."},"et":{"ABT    1436–":"umbes 1436–Surnud","1436–Female":"1436–Surnud","1553–Male":"1553–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1415–Male":"1415–Surnud","1505–Female":"1505–Surnud","1415":"1415","1436":"1436","1553":"1553","1430":"1430","1519":"1519","ABT    1436":"umbes 1436","1505":"1505","Wales":"Wales","{Blddn ap Mnrch}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia"},"fi":{"ABT    1436–":"noin 1436–Kuollut","1436–Female":"1436–Kuollut","1553–Male":"1553–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1415–Male":"1415–Kuollut","1505–Female":"1505–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1436":"1436","1553":"1553","1430":"1430","1519":"1519","ABT    1436":"noin 1436","1505":"1505","Wales":"Wal